key_points: The Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department plans to examine data from the black box of Tiger Woods' car following his accident.
Sheriff Alex Villanueva announced the retrieval of the black box during a Facebook Live session.
The data analysis aims to uncover the circumstances at the time of the accident to help determine its cause.
There was no attempt to obtain Woods' blood samples due to a lack of evidence of impairment.
Deputy John Schloegl emphasized the investigation follows regular protocol to ascertain if a crime was committed.
Woods' accident in Rancho Palos Verdes involved his car hitting a sign and a tree before sustaining major damage.
Woods underwent emergency surgery for significant injuries to his right lower extremity.
Sheriff Villanueva stated during a press briefing that Woods would not face criminal charges, deeming the incident an accident.
There's no consideration of misdemeanor charges like reckless driving unless evidence supports such an infraction.
Woods was not tested for impairment at the scene due to the absence of evident impairments.
spokespersons: Alex Villanueva (Sheriff, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department)
John Schloegl (Deputy, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department)
Anish Mahajan (Chief Medical Officer, Harbor-UCLA Medical Center)
